@NODE intro "Hydra Implementation for MAX - Introduction"

  This   program   add   a   bit   of  polish  to  any   MAX's BBS..   a 
Hydra Bi-Directional  transfer  capability.  Once installed any user can 
select  up  to  10  files  to  transfer,  while uploading to a temporary 
directory to you and chatting. All you need to do is install a couple of 
doors  and MUI 3.1 to  use  @{b}HydraComMUI 1.11 @{ub}(supplied) which is made by 
MaXiM ...  if  you  don't  have/don't  want  MUI,  you  can  always  use
@{b}HydraCom1.00@{ub} which doesn't need MUI.
 SModem doesn't need MUI at all, you might be glad to know.

 Hydra,  as if you didn't know, is a protocol with a difference - it has 
the ability  to transfer two files at once.. one in each direction - AND 
you can have a live chat with the remote caller without interrupting the 
transfer.  Transfer  rates  are generally 1580cps each way at 14k4.. not 
the  best  cps  rates  around,  but  when you consider that's BOTH ways,
you're  still  halving  the  time  you're going to be online. Of course, 
being  a  sysop,  you  might not  give a toss.. But it's nice to offer a 
Hydra protocol =) ... Many  users  would  appreciate  being able to send 
their latest files at the same time as downloading yours. And chat!
 With  ISDN  (we all wish!) rates average 7800cps each way with chat, or 
so I've been told!

 Plus  since  v2.00  an  amazing file lister has been added.. Making it
more than a mere protocol door! See below..

 Interested?  Then  you'll  want  to  install  it..  And  if you're not 
impressed, wipe it again. It's your users' loss. 

 SModem  support has now been added. It works in almost the same way as 
HydraCom, except the BBS end needs to be loaded first, so the prompting 
is a little different. The user is told what to do.

 @{b} Addition about Hydra-MAX Enhanced!@{ub}

 Since  v1.40  of this door I've been thinking how good it would be if it 
weren't  just  an  add-on to get  Hydra  on  your BBS, but instead a full 
takeover  door  which  does  everything.  Well,  this is the result. I've 
called  it  Hydra-MAX Enhanced  which isn't very imaginative.. but that's 
all it is really. The meat of the door is still the Hydra handling.
 So..if you're maybe setting up a BBS and can't be bothered to set up the
menu's  needed  then you now don't need to. H-MAX Enhanced will do it for 
you.  Just  set  up  the sections, a config for the door to tell it about 
them  and  leave it to it. Add a line with `ENHANCED' in the Hydra.CFG to 
enable it.. See the configs page for more info.
 You do of course need to do the ANSI =)
 It  is quite memory hungry too, LZX bundling will probably not work with
2Mb or less. HydraCom  may  also  have  problems, however the rest of the
door will - SModem will be fine, tried and tested.

 The  enhanced  door  does  take a lot of setting up, but it's worth it.. 
All  you  need  to  do  really  is edit the Area.CFG to suit you, and the 
Hydra.CFG - then  load  it and see what happens. Make sure you've got all 
the Compulsory text files too. Boring examples are provided.

 You  also  need  to  add  the LogOff  file to your logoff script in MAX. 
Also  included  is  a  LogOffNoOut  which  is the same but doesn't open a 
window. It's  also  fractionally  faster. Therefore far more suited to an 
automated script =)

@{i}NOTE@{ui} : HydraCom  isn't  perfect. It's not my fault. Ok? Occasionally you 
will find that  a file being sent one way stops - and doesn't resume for 
over 30 mins. I've had it happen myself and boy.. is it annoying!

@ENDNODE

@NODE install "Hydra Implementation for MAX - Installation" 

 You can simply run the Install script, or ...


@{b}If you are not planning to run the Enhanced version, you can skip all
the parts which have an asterisk (*) beside them.@{ub}

 1) Make some new directories :
          BBS:Temp_Receive/        (or appropriate to TEMP)
          BBS:Doors/Hydra/
          BBS:Doors/Hydra/Configs/
          BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/
        * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Users/
        * BBS:FileAreas/
        * BBS:TempArc/
    Also ensure RAM: and T: exist (they ought to do!) for temp files etc.

    ALSO : Make an assign for HYDRA: which points to ALL the executables I 
made, ie HYDRA_ENHN ; LogOff ; LogOffNoOut

    Add it to your startup-sequence or to your Assign Lister.

    It would be sensible to leave them in Doors:Hydra/ and make the assign to 
here. This assignment is used to run LogOffNoOut from within the program.
    This is not essential, but preferable.. The main program, HYDRA_ENHN, 
will check that the assign has been made, and if not, it will quit.

 2) Copy all the files in the directories you unpacked to the relevant 
directory in BBS:Doors/Hydra/
    The result should look like this : @{"SAMPLE HYDRA/ DIR" link "sdir"}

 3) Copy all the files in the provided C/ drawer from the archive into 
your  own  C:  or any other place where a standard Shell can find them 
without a supplied path.

 4) Create or edit these config files :
          @{"BBS:Doors/Hydra/Configs/Hydra.CFG" link "config"}
          @{"BBS:Doors/Hydra/Configs/Files.CFG" link "filescfg"}
        * @{"BBS:Doors/Hydra/Configs/Area.CFG" link "areaconfig"}
        * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Configs/Access.CFG   @{i}Regd version only@{ui}

 5) Create or edit these ANSI screens :
@{i}          # denotes  a  non-compulsory  file, IE  if it's not there the 
          program will use a boring default display. @{ui}

      # * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/ArchiveList
            Non  compulsory  and  for Enhanced only, yep =) This is the 
            same  as  ListingScreen except it is displayed when listing 
            the  contents  of an archive. Also there are less commmands 
            available when in archives.
                In archives you can :
                 [M]ark File
                 [R]ead Text File
                 [L]ook at File_ID.diz
                 [D]ownload Marked Files/Selected File

      # * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/Archiving
            Shown  when  the compressor is at work archiving the marked 
            files. NOTE  on  slow processors this can take a long time. 
            You  should  make sure this is clear on the screen to avoid 
            users hanging up as there is no way to abort the compressor.

       *  BBS:Doors:Hydra/Display/BundleOptions
            This  is  a  basic  table  displaying  some  pretty useless
            information  about  the  archive which has been created and
            the files which are in it, so the user can compare them for
            no  reason  other  than  entertainment =) Makes interesting
            reading I suppose ;)

       #  BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/CheckUploads
            Shown  while  looking  for  uploads in BBS:Temp_Receive/ or 
            whatever  you  specified  in  Hydra.CFG - it  flashes  past
            pretty  quickly  so  use  a  %Y to slow it down if you want 
            anyone to actually see it ;)

          BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/DescribeFiles
            This  is  basically a blank screen =) It has just two lines
            at  the  top which are the titles of 3 columns, ALL YOU CAN
            DO  is  change  the  colours.  LEAVE IT WELL ALONE! This is 
            shown  when  the user is describing their uploads. They can
            enter  up to 50 characters, and describe up to 25 files. If
            they  uploaded  more,  they  will be ignored until the next
            user uploads, then HE will get to describe them! I'm fixing
            this.

       *  BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/FileAreas
            This  is  a list of your File areas for the users to choose 
            from in the lister (Enhanced version) - use AREA numbers as 
            defined  in  the  @{"Area.CFG" link "areaconfig"} to number the areas, not section 
            numbers or anything else.

       *  BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/FileInfo
            A  short file explaining what the File Information function 
            does  and  expects  to  be  entered.  All  it requires is a 
            filename, no area/section. Wildcards are not supported!

       *  BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/ListingScreen
            The  main  screen  file for the Enhanced version, this file 
            must  remain  the  same  in format from line 8 and below to
            line 24  inclusive -  the  filelists  are displayed in this 
            space.

       *  BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/MainMenu
            Shown  when first loading with the Enhanced switch on. Look 
            at  the example for the possible keys which can be pressed.
            No  prompt  is  added,  so  put  one in the menu. Leave the
            cursor  where you want the entered letter to appear. It can 
            be enclosed, but leave at least 2 spaces either side so you 
            lose  none  of  the  menu.  The  menu is redrawn after each
            keypress which is not an available key..

       *  BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/NewFilesHelp
            Shown  when  H  is pressed on the NewFiles Scan prompt. See
            the example for the sort of stuff you need to put in it.

       *  BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/NoAccess
            Shown  when  the user tries to perform an action which they 
            have  insufficient  access  for. This screen will not be of 
            much  use  until you register as you cannot define required 
            access levels in an unregistered version.

       #  BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/NoCreds
            If the user has insufficient download credits this is shown 
            to  them  whenever they try to download. The program is NOT
            `generous' - by  this  I  mean  they  must  have one upload
            before they can download at all unless they have a 0:1 rt.
            Example - Rt 4:1  Dns 4  Ups 1  @{b}They cannot download more.@{ub}
                    - Rt 4:1  Dns 0  Ups 2  @{B}They have 8 dl's left.@{ub}

      # * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/NoFiles
            Shown  when  an  area which has no files is entered. Should
            not  normally  appear  because  your file areas will not be 
            empty! Or  so  you hope. If unfound, a line of text will be 
            shown instead. An entry is also made into the log.

      # * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/NoFileID
            Shown  when  no File_ID.DiZ could be found in an archive or 
            supported filetype.

      # * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/NotFound
            Shown when a file in file.data is not actually on the drive 
            to read or download. An entry is also made in the logfile.

      # * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/NoInfo
            Shown  when a file isn't found that the user asked for info 
            on, either through the lister or the main menu. An entry is 
            also made into the logfile.

      # * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/NoMem
            Shown  when the user tries to bundle their marked files but 
            the   host  system  has  insufficient  memory  to  run  the 
            compressor. Use a %Z at the end.

      # * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/NoMarked
            Shown when the user tries to bundle their marked files when 
            they don't have any marked files.

       #  BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/NoUploads
            Shown  if no uploads were found. Maybe a plead for the next 
            time ;) Use %Z at the end once again.

          BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/PreSelect
            Shown before the user starts selecting files from the table 
            in  the  un-enhanced version (also H or D from main menu in 
            the enchanced version) so it should be some help with Hydra 
            and SModem usage and rules, maybe. To keep it onscreen, use 
            a  %Z at the end. This is the first file shown when loading 
            without the Enhanced switch.

       *  BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/RawDown
            Displayed  just  after  you  press  ~  on  the main menu to
            download any file to the user.

       *  BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/Search
            Short  screen on searching help and the format required for 
            the search string.

      # * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/SearchFileAreas
            As  FileAreas  but with an extra line explaining the format 
            for  selecting  areas  to  search. If it doesn't exist then 
            FileAreas will be used.

      # * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/SearchHeader
            This ANSI/ASCII file is pasted onto the beginning of a File 
            Search - use it to customize your BBS  searching.. =)  Best
            to  keep  it  under  15 lines or you'll get no files on the 
            first page ;) I've also had some problems using ANSI, so if 
            your  screen  looks  distorted,  change  it to ASCII. Also,
            don't  put  a Ctrl-L in, or <ESC>2J both of which clear the 
            screen  because  if you do, you lose the control bar at the
            bottom.  It  will re-appear though. If it doesn't exist, no 
            banner  is  put at the top at all. Nothing is added between 
            the  file  and  the list. It would be advisable to put some 
            column headers in too. The first number is the AREA number, 
            then the Filename, Size and Description.

          BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/SelectFiles
            A  table  which  is  displayed while the user selects their 
            files  the old way. Don't alter the layout or position, but 
            you can adjust the feel and colours.

          BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/WantToUpload
            A  prompt for the non-enhanced version - if the user didn't 
            type  any  filenames  in  then  normally  Hydra wouldn't be 
            started,  but if the user presses Y at this screen, it will 
            so they can upload.

      # * BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/Uploading
            Displayed  whenever  a uni-directional upload is initiated.
            Should just inform the user how to quit, or something.


 6) Create or edit these batch files :
        * @{"BBS:Doors/Hydra/Rec.BAT" link "batches"}
        * @{"BBS:Doors/Hydra/???AddAd.BAT" link "batches"}

 7) Install  HYDRA_ENHN  in MAX as a standard door, using Menu Function
34 with no Extra value.

 8) EITHER a) Put LogOffNoOut in your logoff script
        or b) Put LogOffNoOut in a cron script to be run at least every 
               24Hrs

 9) If you register, you can either put the key in S: or BBS:Doors/HYDRA
when you get it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE sdir "Sample HYDRA/ dir"
BBS:Doors/Hydra/
     Users (dir)
       Chris_Elsworth                   M.Default
     Display (dir)
       AccessSettings                   ArchiveList
       Archiving                        BundleOptions
       CheckUploads                     DescribeFiles
       FileAreas                        FileInfo
       ListingScreen                    MainMenu
       NewFilesHelp                     NoAccess
       NoFileID                         NoMarked
       NoMem                            NotFound
       NoUploads                        Online_Help
       PreSelect                        RawDown
       Search                           SearchFileAreas
       SearchHeader                     SelectFiles
       UserPrefs                        WantToUpload
     Configs (dir)
       Area.CFG                         Files.CFG
       Hydra.CFG                        
  Configs.info                     Display.info
  Hydra.GUIDE                      Hydra.GUIDE.info
  HYDRA_CONFIG                     HYDRA_CONFIG.info
  HYDRA_ENHN                       Install
  Install.info                     LhAAddAd.BAT
  LogOff                           LogOffNoOut
  LZXAddAd.BAT                     Rec.BAT
  Users.info  

---
 Don't worry if you don't have all the Display/ files - not all of them 
are required.
 After  running  the  door  in Enhanced mode you will also notice a new
file  appear  in  Users/ - it's  called M.InUse - don't delete it, just 
ignore it, it's used to store the marked files and is reset on each new 
user  coming into the door so doesn't need deleting. Plus lots of small 
files  will  appear,  being  the preference files of your users. Do not 
alter or delete them.
 Also  you  won't  have  HYDRA_ACC_SET_R  as these are registered  only
programs.  HYDRA_ACC_SET_R  is used to set the access  levels  required
to  perform  uploads,  downloads  and  listing in each area seperately,
giving total control.

 After  registering  you will need to create a new config file as well, 
Configs/Access.CFG - details will come with the registered program.
@ENDNODE

@NODE addad "Hydra Implementation for MAX - Advert Batch files"
 These files, if they exist, are executed just before writing the uploaded
files  to  the  file.data  and they can actually do anything you want, but
they are intended to add BBS adverts to archives if you want to add one..

 To  get  one  activated  all  you  have  to do  is  create one similar to 
LZXAddAd.BAT  but replacing the main line which loads LZX with one loading
your  archiver/adder etc.. Replace the first three letters of the filename
with the suffix.
MyFile.LZX ; LZXAddAd.BAT
MyText.TXT ; TXTAddAd.BAT

etc.. It  only  works  for  3  letter  suffixes , so guide is not usuable.
However  you  can use gde and hope no other suffix collides with it in the 
future =)

 Just  edit  the  batch file to suit your requirements. The only arguement
which  is  supplied  is  the  name  and  path of the archive, which can be
utilised  with  .key  as  shown  in  the  examples..

 If  any  one  of  the  batch  files doesn't exist, nothing will be added,
simple.  You can have a batch file for LZX, but none for any other and all
will be fine.

 Note  this  feature  isn't  restricted to archives. It can be used on TXT 
files  etc  with  C:Type >FILE BBS:MyBBSAdvert  to add some text to a text 
file.

@ENDNODE

@NODE config "Hydra Implementation for MAX - HYDRA.CFG file"
 The config file must reside in BBS:Doors/HYDRA/Configs/ and must be called 
HYDRA.CFG

 You  can put these commands in.. each one must have it's own line and be 
terminated  with  a  CR.@{b} Leave a blank line at the end of the file or the 
last line may not be read!@{ub}

 Note the FILE keyword is now gone. See @{"Files.CFG" link "filecfg"}

 If any keyword is defined more than once, the last one will be used.

 @{" NODISPTIME                      " link "cfgtime"}

 @{" ALLOWLZX                        " link "cfgallowlzx"}
 @{" DISPTIME                        " link "cfgtime"}
 @{" ENHANCED                        " link "cfgenh"}
 @{" EXTERNAL                        " link "cfgext"}
 @{" FORCEUPLOAD                     " link "cfgforce"}
 @{" LINE                            " link "cfgline"}
 @{" LOCK                            " link "cfglock"}
 @{" LOGFILE                         " link "cfglfile"}
 @{" LOGLEVEL                        " link "cfglog"}
 @{" SERIAL                          " link "cfgser"}
 @{" TEMP                            " link "cfgtemp"}
 @{" UNIT                            " link "cfgunit"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE cfgallowlzx "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     ALLOWLZX@{ub}           default off
 This  keyword  allows  the users to select LZX as a Marked File Bundling 
method  if  it  appears in the config. If it doesn't, they are restricted 
to LhA  which  needs  less  memory..  If  you don't have enough memory to 
compress the files nothing will happen. eg;

ALLOWLZX

@{i}Effective only in Enhanced mode!@{ui}  eg;
@ENDNODE

@NODE cfgtime "Hydra Implementation for MAX - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     (NO)DISPTIME@{ub}       default off
 If  in  the  config, this switch turns on the time display in the Lister 
window of the Enhanced version. If it's not in, the time will not appear,
speeding up  operation  slightly.  The result is stored in the User Prefs 
file  until  they  change it.. ie if you specify DISPTIME, the users will 
have it on as default.

DISPTIME

If  you specify NODISPTIME then the Time display cannot be switched on at
all.

NODISPTIME

@{i}Effective only in Enhanced mode!@{ui}  eg;
@ENDNODE

@NODE cfgline "Hydra Implementation for MAX - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     LINE@{ub}           default 14400
 Used to estimate the transfer times.. and is also passed to HydraCom.
 Determines the most likely LINE SPEED. If you have a 14k4 then it'll be 
14400 more often than not.  eg;
LINE 14400
LINE 28800
@ENDNODE

@NODE cfglock "Hydra Implementation for MAX - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     LOCK @{ub}          default 19200
 Determines the LOCKED BAUD RATE which is in MAX's Modem Settings.
 Set to 19200 if unsure (the default anyway)! eg;
LOCK 38400
LOCK 2400
@ENDNODE

@NODE cfgser "Hydra Implementation for MAX - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     SERIAL @{ub}:       default serial.device
 Tells  Hydra  which  serial  device  you're using. Must match the one in
MAX's Modem settings ... eg;
SERIAL 8n1.device
SERIAL artser.device
@ENDNODE

@NODE cfgforce "Hydra Implementation for MAX - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     FORCEUPLOAD @{ub}   default 20
 Tells the program which MAX section to put uploads in. It will probably 
crash  if you specify a non-file section. Default 20 for the sole reason 
that's my Files to Sysop section. eg;
FORCEUPLOAD 1
FORCEUPLOAD 25

@{i} Enhanced Only addition @{ui}

 If you have the Enhanced mode enabled you can opt to allow the user to 
upload  to  the section they are currently listing. Just specify 999 as 
the section to upload to. eg;

FORCEUPLOAD 999

@ENDNODE

@NODE immedupd "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     IMMEDUPD @{ub}      default off
 If  this  is  in  the config, LogOffNoOut will be run after each upload 
to  keep  the  filebase  up to date. This means you don't need to run it 
after  logoff  too.  I  strongly  recommend you leave this option on, or
users  will  have  trouble  browsing  files  after an upload, it behaves
strangely with it off. Having said that, the default is off.. Oops =)
Maybe I ought to change that... eg;

IMMEDUPD

@ENDNODE

@NODE cfgtemp "Hydra Implementation for MAX - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     TEMP @{ub}          default BBS:Temp_Receive/
 Where  to  put  the  uploads as they come in (directory) - they will be 
moved to the Main Path as specified in MAX and put in the filebase after 
the transfer. You should specify a trailing slash - the program will add 
one if it's not there, but be safe eh? =) It must already exist.
@{b} Make sure this directory is EMPTY. The program will delete ALL files in 
it.

 It must exist.
@{ub}

TEMP File:Temp/
TEMP DH1:TempDir/
@ENDNODE

@NODE cfglog "Hydra Implementation for MAX - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     LOGLEVEL @{ub}      default 3
 How much logging to do - ranges from 1 to 5 and uses the Hydra.Log file
 For a breakdown see @{"Logging Levels" link "loglevs"} eg;
LOGLEVEL 1
LOGLEVEL 4
@ENDNODE

@NODE cfglfile "Hydra Implementation for MAX - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     LOGFILE @{ub}       default Doors:Hydra/Hydra.Log
 Specifies the PATH and NAME of the logfile. You must specify both path
and name when configuring your own. eg;

LOGFILE BBS:Logfiles/HYDRA.Log
LOGFILE Logs:Hydra.Log
@ENDNODE

@NODE cfgext "Hydra Implementation for MAX - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     EXTERNAL @{ub}      default HydraCom
 Whether to use SModem or HydraCom. Not required if you're going to use 
HydraCom.  Only  the first letter is actually read (S or H) - note that 
this  command doesn't determine the one-and-only mode that can be used, 
but it  determines  the default mode. Users may change what they use if 
they wish. eg;

EXTERNAL SMODEM
EXTERNAL S
EXTERNAL H
@ENDNODE

@NODE cfgenh "Hydra Implementation for MAX - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     ENHANCED @{ub}      default off
 Put  this in the config to enable the Enhanced mode (Lister and ZModem 
etc) Takes  no  arguements  or  strings.. Leave it out to revert to the 
original Hydra-MAX. eg;

ENHANCED
@ENDNODE

@NODE cfgunit "Hydra Implementation for MAX - HYDRA.CFG file"
@{b}     UNIT @{ub}           default 0
 The serial unit to use. Only change if you have a serial card and you're 
using an additional port.. Ranges from 0 >>>  eg;

UNIT 0
UNIT 3


You can use nullmodem.device for testing now - simply set nullmodem.device 
unit 2 in MAX and H-MAX and nullmodem.device unit 3 in NComm/Term.

@ENDNODE

@NODE externals "Hydra Implementation for MAX - External Programs"

@{b} Transfer programs and paths..@{ub}
     HydraCom must be in your search path

     Version of HydraCOM supplied   :   1.11 .. @{b}requires MUI 3.1 @{ub}!
      The  standard Hydra fare door. Works equally well on either side of 
      the connection, caller or BBS. Slow on 020's or below. Buggy.

     SModem must be in your search path  

     Version of SModem supplied     :   1.00r3 .. doesn't need MUI! =))
      A newer entrant into bi-directional transfer. Tends to be faster 
      than  HydraCom  but does sometimes get lots of errors. Suited to 
      slow machines (020 and even below is fine). New version supplied 
      from HM 2.00 which should be better.

@{b} Other programs and paths.. @{ub}

   DMS                              (in your search path)
     Used to get info on a DMS archive.


@{i}  These are needed to get the relevant File_ID.DIZ's@{ui} (Enhanced Only)

   DMSDescript                      (in your search path)
     Extracts DMS File_ID's

   EXEDescript                      (in your search path)
     Extracts Executable File_ID's

   GIFDesc                          (in your search path)
     GIF File_ID extractor

   LhA @{b}(not supplied)@{ub}               (in your search path)
   LZX @{b}(not supplied)@{ub}               (in your search path) 
     Both used to list, enter and extract File_ID's.

   ModuleDescript                   (in your search path)
     Gets File_ID's from modules

   TXTExtract                       (in your search path)
     Gets File_ID's from texts

 LhA and LZX are not supplied. I assume you have them? =)

@ENDNODE

@NODE loglevs "Hydra Implementation for MAX - Logging Levels"

 3  is  the  best  ratio  between info and size, while 4 is better if you 
want  to  know  more  about  what's  happening.  1  and 2 tell you almost 
nothing. 5 is full of minor notes which you won't need at all.

Experiment  till  you  find a suitable level - when reporting bugs always 
use 5 and send me your log describing the problem.

@ENDNODE

@NODE filecfg "Hydra Implementation for MAX - FILES.CFG file"
@{b} I've  been  changing  and  restoring the use of this file in every other 
release.  A  bit confusing. BUT now it's done - and it's gonna stay. It's 
funtion  now is to contain paths to check when files weren't found on the 
BBS.@{ub}

@{b} THIS FILE IS NOW COMPULSORY. @{ub}

 This  config  file  was introduced with v1.12 and  allows you to specify 
more  than  one  filepath  to  search  when  looking  for files WHICH ARE 
OFFLINE.
 It  simply  contains  a  list of  directories to scan.
 You can specify up to @{b}500@{ub} directories. Anyone want more?
 Simply type them in, one dir per line..

BBS:Files/SYSOPFILES/
RAM:
NODELIST:
MAIL:Bin/


and  so  on.  You @{b}must put a trailing slash @{ub}and @{b}always leave a blank line 
at the bottom of the file@{ub}, as with the Hydra.CFG file.

@{b} NOTE THAT THIS FILE IS NOT FOR THE PATHS LEADING TO YOUR ONLINE FILES. 
IT  IS  FOR  THE  PATHS  LEADING  TO OFFLINE FILES WHICH YOU DON'T MIND 
FRIENDS  DOWNLOADING. @{ub} ie - NODELIST: if  you  don't  mind  your  mates 
grabbing your nodelist.
@{b} REMEMBER  ALL  USERS  CAN ACCESS THESE PATHS AT THE MOMENT - THEY JUST 
NEED TO KNOW THE FILENAMES!@{ub}

 A  problem  has  been  brought  to my attention by someone who was using 
thirty  odd entries in this file.. It seemed to crash when it was looking 
through  them all.. In fact it hadn't crashed, but it was so busy working 
on  the  directories  it  seemed  as if it had. Please keep the number of 
directories  here to a minimum. Remember you don't need to put BBS:Files/ 
in  here  as  that's  the default path which is used by the MAX File.data 
thus it is automatically searched.
@ENDNODE

@NODE execdesc "Hydra Implementation for MAX - Descriptions"

@{"  HYDRA_ENHN                      " link "enhance"} Fully Enhanced version

@{"  HYDRA_ACC_SET                   " link "accset"} Sets access for areas
                                     Registered users only..

@{"  HYDRA_CONFIG                    " link "confexe"} A GUI based config program


@{"  LOGOFF                          " link "logoffdoor"} Execute this on logoff

@{"  Batch files..                   " link "batches"}

@{"  Other External Programs         " link "externals"} File_ID extractors..
@ENDNODE

@NODE confexe "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - Hydra Config Program"
 This  Gadtools-GUI  based  program  is for settings the parameters of the
config  files  HYDRA.CFG -  FILES.CFG -  AREA.CFG  (and  ACCESS.CFG   when
registered)  easily  without  even having to look at a text editor. Simply
run it from the supplied icon and point and click.

 The  blanked  out gadgets are either not finished/available to registered 
users only.

 For help on what the settings do, check the section in this guide related
to configuring the text files - the gadgets are almost the same.

 When setting your Files.CFG paths, put them in order of preference.

 When setting Area.CFG lists, the top area is area 1, then 2, etc.

 Access.CFG  has  a listview with all the areas defined from the Area.CFG
listing  -  for each entry there are three boxes, to set access for List, 
Upload and Download. All the other icons and utilities on this screen are
incomplete.
@ENDNODE

@NODE batches "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - Batch files"
 These AmigaDOS scripts are executed at various times and allow you to
customise the way HM works to a certain extent..

All batch files go in BBS:Doors/Hydra/ which  should  also  be  assigned
as HYDRA:


Rec.BAT                       - executed to start an XPR upload.
@{"LZXAddAd.BAT" link "addad"}                 - executed just before adding the file to the
@{"LhAAddAd.BAT" link "addad"}                   file.data to add BBS adverts to the various
@{"ZIPAddAd.BAT" link "addad"}                   types of archive.

In all cases there is an example provided, please look at it!

@ENDNODE

@NODE logoffdoor "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - LogOff description"
 This  small  door  must be run before you first load Hydra-MAX Enhanced 
and  put in your logoff script, or midnight run script. It must at least 
be  run regularly.  What it does is make several files in BBS:FileAreas/ 
which  are  small clones of the file.data but split into chunks by area. 
This  makes  accessing  the files much much faster and makes speedy file 
searching  possible.  Also  included  is  LogOffNoOut  which is the same 
but  doesn't  open  an output window - this makes it fractionally faster 
and better for unassisted running.

Requires the path BBS:FileAreas/
Requires the file.data and file.index to be in the path specified as the 
Main File Path in MAXsBBS.
@ENDNODE

@NODE accset "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - Access Setter"
@{i}          Access Setter - Part of the Hydra Protocol Door@{ui}

 This  program,  also  to  be  run as  a door, is for setting the access 
required to List, Upload, and Download in each individual section.
 By  default  every  area  you  specify  has  List  and  Download access 
requirements of 10, and Upload access is 0. It is not possible to change 
these  presets  in  the  unregistered  version. Registering will get you 
this  program  which  generates  a  file  to customize them. I will also
provide  details  on the format of the file it makes so you can directly 
edit  each  area  without  loading  this  program. Either way, you gotta 
register  first =) Therefore   do   not  put  your  Sysop  Area  on   an 
unregistered  Hydra-MAX. I  will  not  be  responsible for private files 
downloaded by users.

 When registered, this is how you use it:

 You  will  see  a  table  (BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/AccessSettings)  and 
each value for Upload/List/Download has a letter next to it - press this 
letter to type in a new value for the corresponding access setting.
 Since  only  10 areas are displayed on the table, you must press < or > 
to see more. Press 0 to save, or - to abort the new settings. If no file 
exists  to  tell  Hydra-MAX  what  access levels to use, the defaults of 
List = 10, Download = 10 and Upload = 0 will be used.


@ENDNODE

@NODE areaconfig "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - Area Translations"
 This  file  is  ESSENTIAL.  It tells the door what sections of MAX are
in  use  and  what Area number relates to them. It is only essential if
you have ENHANCED selected by the way =)
 To  show you what I mean.. In the door there is a text file shown upon 
loading,  (FileAreas)  which is a list of the File Areas available. You 
will not want to put in the actual Section numbers which relate to them 
unless  you're  very  organised  and  they  start at 1, and increase in 
alphabetical  order  to  the  last one. If that is the case by the way, 
sorry,  you'll  still  have  to do this, but it'll be easy anyway. What
you're  going  to want to do is let the user type 1 to get at the first 
area  and  say,  50 for the last one if you've 50 file areas. Yes? Well 
this file is just for that.
 This  is how you do it. It's simple. The FIRST line of the file is for 
the  Area 01. So.. Area 01 is going to be, Files To Sysop? Yep. Ok, now 
my Files To Sysop is actually Section 20 in MAX. So on the first line I 
type 20.
 The  SECOND  line  will  be for Area 02. And so on. You'll end up with 
this...

---
20
21
22
23
24
etc etc etc

---
 If your file sections begin at 20 and go up, like mine do. Or this..

---
20
64
1
6
76
34
etc etc etc

---
 If they're scattered all over the place. Whatever they're like, that's 
what  you have to do for this file. Leave at least 3 blank lines at the 
end. They won't be interpreted as blank areas, don't worry ;)

 You  must switch on the From: field for all the File Areas you wish to 
use, too, otherwise  H-MAX  won't recognise or use them properly. There
is no option for anonymous uploads in H-MAX yet anyway. The only way to 
find out who uploaded a file is to use the unfinished File Information.

 Then  make a screen to display the Areas, and you're done. There is an 
example but I'm sure you'll agree the Areas are wrong anyway =)
@ENDNODE

@NODE enhance "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - Executable Description"
@{i}          Hydra-MAX Enhanced Hydra Protocol Door@{ui}

 Whoa.. Where do I start? =)

 Let's  just  say  if  you were to install this door properly, you could 
throw  away  all  your  MAX  File menus and never need to use Upload and 
Download menu functions again, or Listing for that matter =)

 So.. Load it, play with it, then choose a topic :

 @{"Viewing Functions       " link "viewfunc"}
 @{"Archive Functions       " link "arcfunc"}
 @{"Transfer Functions      " link "transfunc"}
 @{"User Preferences        " link "userprefs"}

 @{"File Searching          " link "filesearching"}

 @{"NewFiles Scanning       " link "newfiles"}

 You  will  find many references crop up twice, three times, if they are 
related  to  both  Viewing  and Archiving for example. [V]iew Archive is 
one of them.

 Twitting works fully in nearly all places.

 Options from the main menu are as follows..

[H] - This  makes  the  program  act  as  if ENHANCED was not put in the 
config,  and  pops  up  the table (after Display/PreSelect) so users can 
mark files if they know the filenames.

[N] - @{"NewFiles scan." link "newfiles"}

[D] - Very  similar  to  the  old  Hydra-MAX door, except it uses an XPR 
library  to send the files, NOT Hydra/SModem. The library is selected in 
the [P]references in the lister, or from Main Menu.

[M] - Sends marked files (useful for NewFiles-Scan sending)

[U] - Uploads file(s) after  asking the user for an area number. Uploads 
are  processed  in the  same way as normal, dupe-checked, length-checked 
and then added to  the filebase. The filearea (unless FORCEUPLOAD is set
to a real filearea) is determined by the current area.

[S] - Searches  the filebase for a specified piece of text, or looks for 
any  files  NOT containing the text (not that that's going to be used!). 
The user specifies the areas to be searched on a single line ie:
1 2 3 6 8
OR  they   can  just  press   A   to   search   ALL   fileareas.   Reads
Display/SearchFileAreas which should be the same as FileAreas but with a 
helpful line detailing how to use the search area procedure.

[I] - Information on file.  The user needs to type in the filename only,
no  area/section  number is required. It returns information on the file
such as Uploader, Size, Area/Section and Path.

[L] - Enters  the  Enhanced door  proper..  Lists  files  from  the area
selected from the menu file which was selected at logon.

[~] - Raw download - pops  up  an Asl file requester so you can select a
file  to send using XPR, quickly. Ratio's are not checked, downloads are
not  increased,  access is not checked. However there is no way a remote
user  can  select  themselves a file, so the best they can do is lock up
your BBS till you see it. Access checking is left out because if it were
in, you would have to set their access to 10,000 each time you wanted to
raw download! Not good.

[P] - User Preferences, same as P from the File Listings.

[Q] - Quits to the BBS.

@ENDNODE

@NODE newfiles "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - NewFiles Scan"
 This  function  lists  new  files,  either since x days ago or since last
logon, read on for more info.

 When  selected, the  user  gets  a  prompt  asking what type of search to
perform. The choices are :

[x]  - Enter a number to search for files uploaded in the last x days.

[L]  - Last on, search  for files the user hasn't had a chance to see, ie,
uploaded between the time the user was last on and now. Accurate to within
one  minute..  If  the user logged off at 11:39 on any one day, and a file
was sent at 11:39 on the same day (quick user!) then it won't be picked up.
Not going to be a problem though, is it? Really? =)

[H]  - Help, displays a short help file in the Text Reader, see the example
and note it must be called BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/NewFilesHelp  !


 Note that the scan is Global, ie, it searches all fileareas.


 @{b}When  searching@{ub},  a  filearea  is  searched at a time, and any matches are
displayed at the end of each area. Now, the user can do the following..

[D]ownload one of the files shown - the user has to enter the number beside
the file they want and it will be XPR'ed to them.

[M]ark File - add  the file to the marked list. If you Mark a file then you
can  enter  the  lister  (enhanced mode) and Hydra/SModem the file down, or
just batch download it after you finish browsing.

[A]bort - Quits the entire scan.

[S]kip Area - skips the rest of the area if more files are to be listed and
starts on the next one.

[C]ontinue (Return also) - carries onto the next page/area

@ENDNODE

@NODE filesearching "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - File Searching" 
 On  the main menu is an option to search the files for a string of text 
either in or not in the filenames and descriptions. Default action is to 
search  filenames  and descriptions for text entered. If the user adds a 
tilde (~)  to  the  beginning  of  the text the action is reversed - all 
filenames and descriptions NOT containing the text will be shown.
 When selecting the area to search, typing @{b}A@{ub} and pressing Return will 
seach all areas.

 Note that wildcards are not required. Just type in a string.

 To specify an area to search, or multiple areas, just type them in, 
seperated by a space, at the next prompt. NOTE you don't type the actual 
section  number, but the Area number as defined by Area.CFG - entering 1 
here  refers  to  line  1  of this cfg file, and the number on that line 
calls the relevant section.

eg;

1 2 13 3

 No  specific  order  is  required.  The  areas will be searched in that
order. The search cannot be stopped (yet).

 Typing @{b}A@{ub} searches all areas in ascending numerical order.


 The  list  is  put  in  a  file  in RAM: and displayed through the text 
reader. Any calls for it to be downloadable??

 Soon to come - an option to search the files IN ARCHIVES. It would then 
be  possible  to  search  all  the LZX and LhA archives for one specific 
file, and once found, bundle it in it's own archive and download it. All 
this  would  take  less  than  10  seconds.. With a moderate filebase of 
course. On  average  50 files are scanned a second, not including inside 
archives.

@ENDNODE

@NODE viewfunc "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - Viewing Functions"
 This  is  a  list of descriptions of functions related to viewing files
etc...

 Most of them are self explanatory.. but here we go.. =)

@{b}[I]nfo@{ub}
 The  same  as [I] from the Main Menu except you don't need to enter the
filename now, the file under the cursor is used.


@{b}[V]iew Archive@{ub} 
 Merely  lists  the  contents  of an archive in the text reader. You can
scroll  up  and  down  and perform the normal text viewing functions.
 Currently working for:
     LhA
     LZX


@{b}[R]ead Text File@{ub}
 Loads  the  selected  file  into the text viewer. While it is perfectly 
possible  to  load  hex files (executables, libraries etc) into the text 
viewer  it  is likely to cause a crash, or simply be rejected. Scrolling 
up  and down is possible, as is Goto Line. Use the keypad number keys to 
move  the  cursor  left  and  right,  and  SPACE selects the highlighted 
option.


@{b}[L]ook at File_ID.diz@{ub}
 Investigates  the  selected file and checks it for a File_ID.DIZ and if 
found,  extracts  it,  and  views  it  using MAX menu function 22. Since 
they're  only  15  lines  or  so  long,  it's not worth loading the text
viewer.  Works  in archives, and on archives of course.. These filetypes 
are supported..   LZX  LhA  DOC/TXT/MAN  MOD/MED  EXE  DMS  GIF 

 It figures it out by filenames...      so be normal with filenames! =)

Type      Search Criteria
~~~~      ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
LZXs;     Last 3 being equal to     LZX
LhAs;                               LhA  (case independent, as are all)
Docs;                               DOC/TXT/MAN
DMS's;                              DMS
GIFs;                               GIF
Modules;                            MOD/MED    (or first three)
EXE;                               @{i} Tries if no other was found.@{ui}


@{b}[W]hat's Marked?@{ub} 
 Shows  the list of marked files and their sizes in the text viewer. Very 
basic at the moment. Will be subject to improvement.


@{b}[?] Help@{ub}
 Displays  the  file  BBS:Doors/Hydra/Display/OnlineHelp if it exists. You could 
PowerSnap  this  section  of the guide or something. If it doesn't exist 
the user is plonked back to the listing.

@ENDNODE

@NODE arcfunc "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - Archive Functions"
 Anything connected to archives will appear below...

@{b}[E]nter Archive@{ub}
 Now  we're  talking..  This  looks  in  the  archive and treats it as a 
directory  or  file  section. You can perform most of the functions that 
you  would  do  in  a  normal  file  area. 
 You can :
  [M]ark File
  [R]ead Text File
  [L]ook at File_ID.diz
  [D]ownload Marked Files/Selected File

 Currently working for:
     LhA
     LZX


@{b}[V]iew Archive@{ub}
 Merely  lists  the  contents  of an archive in the text reader. You can
scroll  up  and  down  and perform the normal text viewing functions. It 
works best for LhA at present, LZX doesn't have a very friendly layout.
 Currently working for:
     LhA
     LZX


@{b}[B]undle Marked@{ub}
 More  cream. This takes all the marked files and packs them into an LZX 
or LhA archive, providing you have enough memory to run LZX with the BBS 
loaded.  Experience shows you will need 2.5Mb of memory to easily manage 
this, although it's possible with 2Mb - but you'll be lucky.
@ENDNODE

@node transfunc "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - Transfer Functions"
 Transfer functions and file marking functions...

 Note  the  user's  Downloads/Uploads/Ratio  are  grabbed from the BBS, so 
use those to alter ratio's etc.

@{b}[M]ark File@{ub}
 Marks  or  unmarks a file for download. You can mark up to 100 files then 
you  have  to  do  a download to clear them. Unmark a file by pressing [M] 
over it when it's marked.


@{b}[W]hat's Marked?@{ub}
 Shows  the  list of marked files and their sizes in the text viewer. Very 
basic at the moment. Will be subject to improvement.


@{b}[C]lear Marked Files@{ub}
 Erases the list of marked files in case they didn't get wiped after 
bundling or downloading (remember this program isn't finished!) or if you 
just made a cockup.


@{b}[D]ownload File(s)@{ub}
 Initiates  a  Uni-Directional  file  transfer with the selected protocol. 
You  must  have  the  relevant  xpr  library. XPRD  is  used to handle the 
transfer. It must be in C:
 Marked  files  are  sent, and  if  none are found, the currently selected 
file. If marked files are found, the selected file is not sent.
 The  sent  files  are  entered  into  the  DnLoadLog.text  (must  be   in 
BBS:Logfiles/ at the moment)

@{b}[U]pload File@{ub}
 Initiates  an  Uni-Directional  upload  with  the selected protocol. Uses 
AsXpr  again.  The file is placed in the current section, if no @{"FORCEUPLOAD" link "cfgforce"}
was  specified.  If  FORCEUPLOAD  was specified then the file is placed in 
the section specified by FORCEUPLOAD.
 To get the upload, an external batch file is launched... 
BBS:Doors/Hydra/Rec.BAT
 It  should  basically  load  an  external  transfer  program  and  put the 
uploads  in  the directory specified by the TEMP keyword, BBS:TEMP_RECEIVE/
by default. There is one supplied which works fine, and uses XPRD.


@{i}@{b}[H]ydra/SModem Xfer@{ub}@{ui}
 The cream of the door. The icing on the cake. Or something.
 Initiates  a  bi-directional  transfer using HydraCom or SModem depending 
on  the  users choice by priority. If they have not altered their setting, 
it  will  be what you specified in @{"EXTERNAL" link "cfgext"} in the Hydra.CFG
 The  marked  files  are sent, if none then the selected file. All uploads 
are placed using the same procedure as in [U]pload File - see above.


@{b}[B]undle Marked@{ub}
 More  cream. This  takes  all the marked files and packs them into an LZX 
or  LhA  archive, providing you have enough memory to run LZX with the BBS 
loaded.  Experience  shows  you will need 2.5Mb of memory to easily manage 
this, although it's possible with 2Mb - but you'll be lucky.
@ENDNODE

@NODE userprefs "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - User Preferences"

@{b}[P]references@{ub}
 Enters the User Preferences screen. A bit sparse at the moment.

 It contains :

@{" [A] Marked File Bundling Method       " link "markedfilebundling"}
@{" [B] Bi-Directional Transfer program   " link "bidirprogram"}
@{" [C] Uni-Directional Transfer protocol " link "unidirprotocol"}
@{" [D] Display time in Lister            " link "time"}
@{" [E] No use yet....                    " link "maintain"}
@{" [F] List Display Routine              " link "disprout"}

 defaults ;    [A] LZX
               [B] Hydra
               [C] Z-Modem
               [D] No
               [E]
               [F] By Row (nicer)

All switches work on a toggle basis. If there are more than two options 
then a cycle is used.

@ENDNODE

@NODE markedfilebundling "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - User Preferences"
 Under Marked File Bundling there are currently two options,

@{b}     LZX@{ub}
           LZX  is  a  very  good  compressor  but requires about 600k of 
memory  for  it to work properly. Not yet available on the PC, but if you 
have the memory and you are an Amiga-Specific board, far better than LhA.

@{b}     LhA@{ub}
           LhA on the other hand is not as good at compressing by a long 
chalk  but  it  will  work  in  400k  or  maybe  less,  and PC users can 
decompress it.

Are there any calls for ZIP, Arc, or Warp...??? Thought not =)
@ENDNODE

@NODE bidirprogram "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - User Preferences"
 Two possible settings at the moment for Bi Directional transferring, 
and they are :-

@{b}     Hydra  @{ub}
              uses  HydraCom (needs MUI) and is sometimes unreliable, 
slow  interface - has  been  known  to crash but otherwise good. Nice 
looking  but  unfortunately  not  up  to  much  underneath on low end 
machines. Avg 1550cps each way at 14k4.

@{b}     S-Modem @{ub}
              uses it's own program, no  MUI required, very fast both 
ways,  but  sometimes  can  generate  countless errors when trying to 
transfer both ways. See if your modem likes it, it doesn't like mine.
Better than Hydra on low end machines. Claims a 99.5% efficiency rate.
This  is  a  good protocol to use even for one way transfers when you
are  sending long files as it's faster than Z-Modem! Avg 1720cps each
way at 14k4.

@ENDNODE

@NODE unidirprotocol "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - User Preferences"
 XPR protocols are possible by using the xpr libraries. If you want any 
other XPR lib included so it can be used, drop me a line and I'll put it 
in. These are the only ones I use often...

 Three possible options for normal Uni Direction transfers, being - 

@{b}     Z-Modem @{ub}
              Standard  protocol,  in  use  by  virtually  every BBS.
Requires  the xprzmodem.library file in LIBS: to work. Avg 1690cps at
14k4.

@{b}     Super Z-Modem @{ub}
              As  above  but  uses blocks of up to 8k (8192b) in size
thus  theoretically  giving  a  speed  increase..  In  practice  it's 
unnoticable,  but  I use it anyway =) Requires the xprszmodem.library
in LIBS: ...  Avg 1690cps at 14k4.

@{b}     Y-Modem @{ub}
              Not  quite  as defunct as some people like to make out,
Y-Modem  can still give Z-Modem a fair run for it's money, especially
on  uncompressed  files,  getting  5000cps  easily  at 14k4. Requires 
xprymodem.library in LIBS: .. Normal use on compressed files averages
1650cps at 14k4.


I  am  not  permitted  to  include any of the above mentioned library
files  in the archive for some copyright reason or other (well no-one
else  does  so  I  thought  I'd  just  stay safe) but they are freely
available  from  just  about  EVERYWHERE. You've probably already got
them.
@ENDNODE

@NODE time "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - User Preferences"
 Simply determines whether the time will be displayed in the lister for 
that  user.. If yes it looks better but is slower, if no  operation  is
faster.
@ENDNODE

@NODE maintain "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - User Preferences"
   There is nothing here =)

@ENDNODE

@NODE disprout "Hydra MAX Enhanced Guide - User Preferences"
 This switch toggles listing between :

@{b} By Row (nicer) @{ub}
         Shows  each  line  at  a  time, first doing Name, Size, Star if 
marked, then Description. The problem with doing it this way is that the 
pen  has to be changed colour very often, slowing output down especially 
on  slow 2400 modems. However this mode does not make mistakes and leave 
stray bits of description like the alternative could do..

@{b} By Column (faster) @{ub}
          This  method  first  displays  all the filenames, then all the 
filesizes, then stars, then descriptions. This way the pen only needs to 
be changed at the end of each column, when going onto the new colour for 
the  next type of data. Theoretically this mode should be faster, and it 
will be noticeable on 2400 systems more than anything else. It also cuts
a couple of corners when redrawing the screen. Very quick.


 Another way to speed up the program generally is to turn off the Time 
Display. If  you  have lots of memory, put all executables in RAM: and
add RAM: to your CLI search path.
@ENDNODE

@NODE regging "Hydra Implementation for MAX - Registration"
 This  program  is  Shareware.  It  is usuable without registering, but a 
registered version has many more benefits and functions etc. You also get
support and boy are you gonna need it =)

 Things disabled in the evaluation version :


You can't set the Access levels for Downloading/Uploading/Listing

There is a 10 second delay before Hydra/SModem transfers start
 and lots more delays besides.

Marked File Bundling




And also..

You  don't  get  support  for  the  program,  or  any personal changes for 
yourself only included. Say you wanted the Main Menu prompt changing..

Registration costs 10ukp.

 Crashmail me 2:250/345 for more details.

 OR the best way of contacting me is via celsworth@borghome.demon.co.uk


I can then send a very small keyfile via Internet E-Mail or whatever.

@ENDNODE

@NODE bugs "Hydra Implementation for MAX - Bugs?"
 Now I get to slag off my own creation =)

 Shouldn't be too hard actually, it is a PUBLIC BETA and BETA's do have
bugs, right? So here goes...

PostScriptum (25.8.96)
Well this list seems to be shrinking a bit =) Version 2.10 was more
bugfixes than anything else, that helped.. I didn't introduce any really
new features, just got rid of those blasted bugs. Still some left though!

     Bugs... 
     ~~~~~~~
 You cannot use Section 0 as a File Area for the simple reason that 
there is no line 0 in the Area.CFG =) I have also developed the entire 
program around starting with Section 1, so .. Sorry. You've only got 99 
possible File Areas, not 100. You try and fit 99 onto one ANSI screen though

@{b} Not  a bug but not a very helpful `feature' - you must turn on the From: 
field  for  all  your  File Areas which you want to use, or they won't be 
recognised or used by H-MAX.@{ub}

 Filenames of less than 5 characters long don't work in the old-style
table I'm afraid.. They are not accepted.

@{b}Known  probs  with  the  lister@{ub} : Searching for text in files is dodgy. I 
know this so don't report it please...


 No other KNOWN bugs which I can't deal with.. There will be some though!
@ENDNODE

@NODE future "Hydra Implementation for MAX - Future Development"
 Things I'm planning for future versions :-

 File Searching IN archives. Be slow though, obviously =(
 Maybe make an index of ALL files which will speed it up.

 Getting rid of TempArc/ etc and just using one tempdir.. easy to do but
tedious.

 File_ID.DIZ support on uploads. Perhaps display the entire lot and ask the
user to pick a line (or 2?) to put in the Description field. Maintaining
compatibility with file.data means I can't show the entire File_ID.DIZ in
the listing.

 Updating the caller log to show uploads and downloads.
 Also making the downloads counter update again.
   OR
 Creating a reqtools window containing information on uploads/downloads and 
ratio, then scrapping the MAX counters. This would appear on Workbench unless 
you run MAXsPro, by Niki Murkett.

 Creating an offline-file-marking system, if Ian Chapman doesn't mind! =)
  This will be good. Log on and grab a compact filelist, feed it into a 
utility you have downloaded previously from within the door, and then use 
this utility to "mark" files offline, then upload the new file produced using 
a special option on main menu. Your marked files are sent.

 Adding CPS displays for uploads/downloads/bidir transfers, to be shown after 
the transfer. Top Ten CPS rates list. Ho hum.

@ENDNODE

@NODE changes "Hydra Implementation for MAX - Changes!"

     Changes as from v2.22   (12/02)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o New screenfile ; HYDRA:Display/Uploading
   This screen is shown whenever a uni-directional upload is initiated.
   An example is included.. The file is  optional,  it  doesn't  have  to
   exist.

 o Now a > character is displayed to the left  of  the  filename  in  the
   lister.  This  is for non-ANSI users who could not see the highlighted
   box over the selected file.

 o The screens HYDRA:Display/ListingScreen & ArchiveList have changed  in 
   appearance. They no longer have vertical lines running down the  sides
   of the main box.

 o The screens HYDRA:Display/FileAreas & SearchFileAreas no longer have a
   prompt added to the end of the file. You have to put one in as part of 
   the file.

 o The  userprefs  files  were  getting bigger by 1 byte with every save,
   this has been fixed ; pref-files will be restored to normal when  next
   saved out.

 o The  directory defined as TEMP is now also used as a working directory
   for the archivers when necessary.


     Changes as from v2.21   (02/02)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Average  CPS is displayed for all uni-directional downloads after each
   transfer. This  calculation  is as accurate as any other CPS display..
   The XPRD.LOG is used to work it out.

 o FileSearch sped up a helluva lot (rewrote entire routine)


     Changes as from v2.20   (26/01 20:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Added @{"UNIT" link "cfgunit"} config keyword.
   Updated HYDRA_CONFIG to reflect this. (v1.1)

 o Instead of using C:Copy to shift uploads around, it  now  uses  C:Move
   This new command is included so copy it to C: ... The  net  result  is
   that uploading processing is infinitely faster provided you have  your 
   temporary directory and your main files  directory ON THE SAME DEVICE.
   @{b}For optimal performance, make this so@{ub}

 o Optimised Archive-Entering routine. It's now  about  10x  faster,  for
   for both LZX and LhA.


     Changes as from v2.19c  (23/01 22:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Changing Areas during Listing files works now.

 o The confirm-download table is now shown when you press D in the lister
   as well as after the table marking. It also appears when  you  have  a 
   file marked and press H for bidirectional transfers. If  there  is  no
   file marked it takes the currently selected one and puts that  as  the
   only entry.

 o The confirm-download table has commas in the file sizes now.


     Changes as from v2.19b  (21/01 10:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Had to disable the DnLoadLog.text maintaining because it  was  causing 
   Illegal Function Calls every time it was called.
   It may be replaced with a custom DownLoadLog.TXT soon.

 o Couple of speed optimisations - this thing flies along  on  my  030/50
   you know =)
   
     Changes as from v2.19a  (08/01/97 16:30)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Fixed  a  horrible  bug  introduced  with the startup information. The
   protocol selected was being changed with data to be printed, hence XPR 
   transfers were not working. Fixed.

 o Contents of TempArc are deleted with each running. Cannot think why  I 
   never did that before. Couldn't be bothered I s'pose =)


     Changes as from v2.19   (02/12 20:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o New  screen   file : @{B}Display/RawDown@{UB} is   displayed   just  after  you 
   press ~ to raw download a file.

 o You can now put the following files in RAM: for quicker access if  you
   have the memory to do so ;
      BBS:MAXsBBS.Config
      BBS:Files/File.Data
      BBS:UserFiles/User.Data

   This will significantly speed up loading time - the  altered  versions
   are  only  put  in  the  original paths at the moment however so add a
   couple of lines to your logoff script to keep the RAM: ones updated.
   Soon you will be able to copy FileAreas/FileXX.Data too.

 o You  now have to assign HYDRA: where the executables are. It no longer
   does it itself.

     Changes as from v2.18   (26/11 22:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Pressing ~ from  the main menu now gives you a filerequester to select
   a file for raw downloading. There is no need to go through the process
   of confirming the choice, etc, the file is selected and sent using the 
   appropriate XPR protocol, whatever the user has selected.
@{B}   ~ is the key above Tab, shifted.@{uB}


     Changes as from v2.17   (10/10 21:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Unreleased internal version


     Changes as from v2.16    (7/10 21:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o You can  now use real cursor-keys for remote cursor moving. However if
   you  hold  down  the  cursors  for  long  enough,  a  file function is
   activated. This is because cursor-key presses are in the form :
      ESC [ A   ESC [ B   ESC [ C  and  ESC [ D
   The  program  is  not  fast  enough  to  process  the  keypresses  and
   interprets the letter as a single keypress. Thus ;
      A = Area Change
      B = Bundle Marked Files
      C = Clear Marked Files
      D = Download Marked
   Sorry  about  this.  The only way to prevent it is to change those key 
   functions..  I  may  well  do  that. Fortunately none of the functions
   which may be executed are very harmful. C & D could be a bit of a pain 
   however..

   This feature possible thanks to Owain Cleaver AKA Lore on MaxsNet2.

 o Additions  to the DnLoadLog.Text are working better now. The CPS  rate
   it calculates still a bit crap though...


     Changes as from v2.15    (07/9 21:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Fixed  the  HYDRA_CONFIG program, now it works without putting rubbish
   in the gadgets, thanks to the extension author!

 
     Changes as from v2.14    (02/9 21:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o You  might  have  noticed some testing lines appear in the config when
   doing  a NewFiles scan - it entered every area number it scanned.. Not
   now, I've removed it..

 o DnLoadLog.text  is  now  updated  with  each  download (not when using
   bi-dir mode yet, just Z-Modem)

 o You  might also have noticed the logline `Average CPS' appear whenever
   a  download  was done.. I forgot to document it ;) Well.. It's been in
   there  since  2.11  (I think)  and  will  be  used  for DnLoadLog.text
   entries. It does not yet appear for downloads made in bi-dir mode.


     Changes as from v2.13    (01/9 18:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Major  rehaul  on  the Main Menu. You now have to select your FileArea
   BEFORE  you perform an operation requiring a filearea (Upload/List). I
   did this because someone quite bluntly told me it was better that way.
   Thanks Pete =) I didn't realise how daft it was really...!

 o You are  shown  the FileArea you are in on the MainMenu now, it's part
   of  the  prompt.  Most of it in fact. If you want a time display (time
   left) you can use a percent-command on the line above..

 o You  also have to select the File Area immediately after loading so no
   twit  can  try  listing  an  area  without  selecting one. You are not
   allowed  to  enter  the program without selecting an area here. Q will
   quit  on  this  first  selection (and  return  to  the  main  menu  on
   subsequent area changes.)

 o The  PreSelect screen was shown (with the old-style table method being
   used)  but  it  should only be shown when Hydra/S-Modem is being used,
   like it does now. Not Z-Modem as it did before.

 o Preferences can be set from the main menu  using  P.  This  saves  you
   having to go into a filearea listing to do it.


     Changes as from v2.11    (28/8 19:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Not  part  of  the  actual  prog,  but  who cares.. I've written a GUI
   interface  to  configure H-MAX with now, but it seems very dodgy after
   a  few  minutes  use  =(  Gadtools  seems  to  get confused and starts
   putting  lots  of junk  in the string gadgets. I've included it anyway
   just  in case my machine was having a bad day ;) If it works for  you,
   great!  If  not,  sorry,  it doesn't for me either. If anyone has  any
   idea why it does this, please tell me. It was written in AmosPro  with 
   the freeware GUIEXT15.LhA extension and GadToolsBox2.0c...
   All  the options which are masked out are not implemented yet,  not in
   the   configurer,  at    least.  The  option's   you'll  see   on  the
   Access-Setter part are not even done in the main program yet!

 o S-Modem didn't work if you used H from the main menu and didn't select
   any  files  to  be  sent.  I  can't @{b}believe@{ub} I did this : I aborted the
   transfer  because the file S-Modem uses to send files was not present!
   Duh! Of course it isn't present, nothing is being sent.... ;) Duuhh!
   Fixed it now.


     Changes as from v2.10    (25/8 22:00)   Major Bugfixing version.
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o @{b}All major releases will now be put on the Aminet (not tiny bugfixes)@{ub}

 o The  filebase  updates  itself  now  after  every  upload  :  you can
   virtually  ignore  the  LogOff and LogOffNoOut executables unless you
   put  a  file in the filebase manually with the Files Editor, in which
   case you need to tell H-MAX about the change with LogOff(NoOut).
   As  a  result, the config keyword IMMEDUPD is completely obsolete. It
   was  going to be optional but it caused more trouble if you didn't do
   it after each upload.. So it's automatic. Erase the line in UserPrefs
   related to Immediate Updating of the Filebase. You can now delete ALL
   references to this keyword.
   @{b}There  is  a slight bug which requires you to change fileareas before
   the new uploads are completely recognised, I'm working on it!@{ub}

 o Unintentional  backdoor  removed  from  Old-style table : by entering
   the  full  path  of a file, ANY file could be downloaded! Sorry.. You
   are now alerted in the logfile if anyone tries this, so you can catch
   anyone who was taking advantage of it.

 o The  Time : display has moved to Line 25, Col 59. (directly down from
   where it used to be)

 o The  Area : display  has moved to Line 25, Col 10. This and the above
   change  make  room  in  the top right corner for a possible real-time
   File_ID.DIZ viewing,  as  you  move  through the files. POSSIBLE, not 
   definite. Quite unlikely, in fact. But this is neater anyway!
 
 o Some   log-messages  have  been  converted  to  better  English,  bad
   grammar removed, etc.

 o The log now tells you what area each upload has been sent to.

 o You  can now Download Marked Files from the main menu, by pressing M. 
   Useful if you just did a newfiles-scan and want to download the files
   you marked in it, without going to a filearea to do it, as you had to.

 o The  program no longer quits if no uploads were found, it now goes to
   the main menu when in enhanced mode.

 o The  NewFiles  scan  introduced in 2.00 now checks that users haven't
   put  a  #  thinking that was correct (instead of a number) and if so,
   informs them that they are doing it wrongly.

 o You  are now told if the logon is a Local or Remote logon, beside the 
   UserName. Also applies in Access Setter (regd only).

 o Possible   bug   where  the  logoff  countdown  could  freeze,  after
   downloading from the Old-Style Table Marking, fixed.

 o Internal error checking put into Access Setter (no more freezing).

 o Possible  `File Already Open'  error  when  uploading with Smodem but 
   not  downloading  any files eliminated. It didn't occur all the time,
   you  probably  never saw it. Good thing, because it caused the entire 
   machine to hang.


     Changes as from v2.01     (7/8 13:10)   @{b}Fourth Aminet Release@{ub}
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Bug  fixed : whenever  anybody  uploaded  lots  of blank file entries
   would  have been generated in 2.00 because of the increased number of
   uploads allowed.. Not now.

 o LogOff  and  LogOffNoOut  are now  written in AmigaE making them MUCH
   smaller  and faster too! =)) The Access Setter is next... =) It won't
   be  a  door  then,  maybe  an Intuition window on Workbench? Comments
   please..  Be quite nice, a GUI to edit the Accesses rather than a BBS
   door.


     Changes as from v2.00     (2/8 13:00)   @{b}Third Aminet Release@{ub}
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Whopping  great  re-write - the door is now called Hydra MAX Enhanced
   It  can  be  made  to  emulate the old door, but please check out the 
   enhanced side, it's cool! MANY changes came about with this re-write.
   Here are some of them.. 

 o Improved the routine which gets the filesizes in the table selector.

 o Twitting works now, properly!

 o [U]ser Options  from  the  Select-By-Name  method  has  gone,  it was 
   useless  and  I  didn't  want  it  anymore,  edit your SelectFiles to 
   reflect this and delete OptionScreen, both in Display/ ...

 o The TEMP  directory  is  now  checked  and if it doesn't exist, T: is 
   used.

 o Some  keywords  have a reverse - NO<keyword> which turns them off, so 
   you don't have to rely on defaults which might change.

 o Sanity  check  added to skip directories which definitely didn't have 
   the requested off-line file in, using Exist().

 o Max number of processed uploads increased to 25.

 o All  external  executables  can  now be put where you like. Hydra-MAX 
   searches the command path to find them.
   To check that they can be found, go into a Shell and type
@{b}     CD RAM:
     <name of prog to search for>@{ub}
   And  provided  the  program  isn't  in  RAM:  the search path will be 
   called.
   To add more paths to the search path, type
@{b}     path <path> add@{ub}
   Or alter the line in your startup-sequence to contain the path of the 
   files.  If  you  don't know what I'm on about here, just dump all the 
   external files in C: and it'll work =)

 o New config keywords related to the Enhanced side of the door. See the 
   config section. ALLOWLZX and DISPTIME are two which spring to mind.

 o New  version  of  SModem  included - rev 3, has  lower  CPU usage and 
   various bugfixes.

 o New config file - Area.CFG - required to run the Enhanced door.

 o Dupe  checking  is  in,  but  it  doesn't  act upon dupes found, just
   overwrites them.

 o @{b}MANY new text files : See guide.@{ub}


     Changes as from v1.42    (29/3 14:40)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Crashed  if no files were present in upload directory. Stupid me.. It 
   tried to process the non-existant file! Sorted.

 o Discovered  it  runs  fine  on most systems accepting Paragon doors..
   It's  a bit strange. Give it a go.. It works alright on my TransAmiga 
   Paragon  Interpreter.  You'll  need to juggle the files a bit to make 
   sure that everything can be found. Make BBS:Doors/Hydra etc.
   You'll  need  a MAXSBBS.Config and File.data plus File.Index too. Ok, 
   so maybe  it's not such a good idea after all then. But it does work.


     Changes as from v1.41    (24/3 12:20)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o FILE  keyword  removed. You now @{b}need@{ub} a @{"Files.CFG" link "filecfg"} so make one and just 
   type RAM: onto one line, and leave several blank ones after it.

 o Space  removed from beginning of filename in the Files Editor of MAX,
   after  a  file  was uploaded there was a stray space in front of each 
   uploaded file.


     Changes as from v1.40    (23/3 19:40)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o SModem support added.
     Enabled by use of new keyword EXTERNAL ..ie
     @{b}EXTERNAL SMODEM@{ub}


     Changes as from v1.32    (21/3 15:20)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o LOGLEVEL  keyword  added.  Allows you to alter the level of logging a 
   bit.

 o Lower case config keywords will work now.

 o The defaults are set correctly when the Hydra.CFG file doesn't exist,
   previously  they were set, but only if the file existed! So you could 
   make  a  blank  file and all would be well. Now you don't need one if 
   the defaults suit you.


     Changes as from v1.31    (20/3 21:50)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o If  the  user  didn't download any files, they didn't get a chance to 
   upload any. They do now, see new text file `WantToUpload'

 o Added  primitive logging. There are no options to turn it up, down or 
   even  off  yet.  It  may  help  you to find out why it keeps quitting 
   itself at one point as it notes when any file is missing.


     Changes as from v1.30    (19/3 18:20)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Uploads now dealt with - they are added to the filebase under Section 
   20  by  default, changeable in the config. Also they are deleted from 
   the temporary directory and put in the Main Path as in MAX.

 o New  text  file - DescribeFiles. Shown when entering descriptions for 
   the uploads.

 o New config keywords :
     TEMP - what temporary directory to use, default BBS:Temp_Receive/
     FORCEUPLOAD - what MAX Section to put uploads in.

 o Lots of optimizing - lots of rewriting.


     Changes as from v1.24    (15/3 14:50)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Added  an advert for myself at startup, also shows the version number 
   more clearly as it's a bit obscure on the final screen.

 o @{b}Access  checking  is now in there.@{ub} If the users access is too high or 
   too  low  then  the  program acts as if the file isn't there. It also 
   displays a line of information on the local screen showing :
    Section of file in question
    Lo-Access of this section
    Hi-Access of this section
    User's Access.
   You can determine from this whether a file is actually missing or the 
   user  doesn't  have  enough  access when a situation occurs where the 
   program  won't mark a file. If the file is there and the user has the 
   access,  you've  found  a bug - please report it, giving all relevant 
   information.

   @{b}This  was  removed  very  quickly  in  a  later  version  as it looks
   terrible =( I can't remember which exactly.@{ub}

 o Hit the 100k barrier =)


     Changes as from v1.23    (9/3 02:05)    @{b}Second Aminet Release@{ub}
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o v1.22  slightly  corrected.  Works  perfectly as far as I can see, as 
   v1.22  should have done. v1.22 didn't know the path to find the files 
   selected from the File.Data - does now.


     Changes as from v1.22    (5/3 17:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o An  hour later... =) I added a feature which allows you to type in as 
   many filenames as you want, which might not be in the BBS, but can be 
   in  any  path  you  specify.  Still  being  developed.  Just type the 
   filename  which  should be available in the path given by FILE and it 
   will be marked. Not beta tested YET.


     Changes as from v1.21b   (5/3 16:00)    @{i}Unreleased@{ui}
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Put  in  a  revised  File-Search routine - now returns much more info, 
   but none of it is used yet. There will soon be a List Files option in 
   the File Selecting stage.. possibly in v1.3

      @{b}NOTE (2/8) v1.3 !! hehehe, try v2.00 - took a while longer than I
      had hoped but it got here in the end! =)@{ub}

 o v1.21 complained that it had no file path if you didn't give it one in 
   the  config  even though  it  didn't use it. You could get round it by 
   giving it any path.. but it's fixed now. Sorry.. Silly mistake.
   That would be the one on Aminet as well wouldn't it?


     Changes as from v1.21    (4/3 21:00)    @{i}First Aminet Release...@{ui}
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Stupid  bug  fixed  in the merging of the new routine and my program - 
   it  allowed  any files to be selected whether they existed or not. Not 
   any more. Reported by the routine programmer, (3/3 23:35)

 o Revised  File-Search  routine  which  goes  part-way  to  putting in a 
   lister when selecting files.. I still need the File Area though.


     Changes as from v1.2     (3/3 21:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o The  FILE  keyword  is  now ignored. Instead of checking a given path, 
   the public door now scans the File.data created by MAX. 

 o ... and it follows that the FILES.CFG file will not be used either in 
   v1.2 at least.

 o Previous  versions  had a noticable delay when using filebases of more 
   than  500  files.  Noticable being 2 minutes.. Ahem. Fixed thanks to a 
   new routine by Karl Naylor.


     Changes as from v1.12    (1/3 22:00)
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o The  config  keyword  `PATH'  has been replaced by `FILE' ... PATH was
   too  general  since I'm going to introduce more paths soon. Check your 
   config and change it!

 o If no `FILE' keyword  is specified in the config, it looks for another 
   config file, named `FILES.CFG' - see the @{"FILES.CFG section" link "filecfg"}

 o The  `Time' column is now correctly aligned when times of over 10 mins
   are  displayed.  Previously  the  colon  was  pushed over by the extra 
   digit.

 o Six figure file sizes had a leading comma! Not any more..


     Changes as from v1.11    (29/2/96 21:00)     @{i}First Release@{ui}
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 o Bugfixes - first release. v1.00 to v1.10 were given only to one BBS.
@ENDNODE

